North River, piers 10 and 11,
West Street, west side, from Carlisle (left) to Albany (right) Streets, showing piers 10 and 11 North River, with the Hudson River and the New Jersey Shore line in the background. At the extreme right is seen a portion of the West Street Building at the N.W. corner of Albany Street and at the extreme left, a portion of the New York Post Building at the
S.W. corner of Carlisle Street.

August 20, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.
title: North (Hudson) River - Piers 10 and 11.

text:
(1) West Street,east side,from Carlisle(right),to Albany(left), Streets,showing a clearance where #80-86 formerly stood. The view is eastward and shows the rear of P.S.#29,a four story structure occupying the remaining half of this block and facing on Washington Street. July 2nd,1937

(2) West Street,north east corner of Albany. The prominent buildings shown across the skyline are the Bank of Manhattan and the Irving Trust Company. July 2nd,1937

Photographs by, P.L.Sperr,
